SIMPLE: j
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: J
<hw>J</hw> <pr>(j⟦amac⟧)</pr>. <def>J is the tenth letter of the English
alphabet. It is a later variant form of the Roman letter I, used to
express a consonantal sound, that is, originally, the sound of English
<xex>y</xex> in <xex>yet</xex>. The forms J and I have, until a recent
time, been classed together, and they have been used
interchangeably.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>In medical prescriptions <xex>j</xex> is still used in place of
<xex>i</xex> at the end of a number, as a Roman numeral; as,
v<xex>j</xex>, xi<xex>j</xex>.</p>

<p>J is etymologically most closely related to <xex>i</xex>,
<xex>y</xex>, <xex>g</xex>; as in <xex>j</xex>ot, <xex>i</xex>ota;
<xex>j</xex>est, <xex>g</xex>esture; <xex>j</xex>oin,
<xex>j</xex>ugular, <xex>y</xex>oke. See <er>I</er>.</p>

<p>J is a compound vocal consonant, nearly equivalent in sound to
<xex>dzh</xex>. It is exactly the same as <xex>g</xex> in
<xex>gem</xex>. See <xex>Guide to Pronunciation</xex>, ⟦sect⟧⟦sect⟧ 179,
211, 239.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<p><ent>Jaal goat</ent>⟦br⟧
